The evidence with the title 'An overview of growing income inequalities in oecd countries ... ' says The Gini coefficient, a standard measure of income inequality that ranges from 0 ( when everybody has identical incomes) to 1 (when all income goes to only one person), stood at an average of 0.29 in OECD countries in the mid-1980s. By the late 2000s, however, it had increased by almost 10% to 0.316. Significantly ... 
